<tableCitation id="C69903737C34FFA4FBB0FA86FB814F5D" box="[1044,1133,1360,1384]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="2.[168,221,1629,1649]" captionText="Table 1. List of sampling sites in the EstaÇÃo Ecológica de TaiamÃ (EET), Pantanal wetland, Brazil, with sampled hydrological cycle, geographic coordinates (at cener point of sites) and predominant macrohabitats." pageId="15" pageNumber="416">Tables 1</tableCitation>
, 
<tableCitation id="C69903737C34FFA4FBDEFA86FB664F5D" box="[1146,1162,1360,1384]" captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="3.[168,221,162,182]" captionText="Table 2. List of birds recorded at EstaÇÃo Ecológica de TaiamÃ (EET), Pantanal wetland, Brazil. Legend: Migratory status (Somenzari et al. 2018): resident (RDT), migratory (MGT), partially migratory (MPR), vagrant (VAG), and not defined (ND). Occurrence status of this study: very frequent (100–75%), frequent (74–50%), reasonably frequent (49–25%), less frequent (&lt;25%), and infrequent for non-systematic data (IN). Record type (Carlos et al. 2010): IO = indication of occurrence (species not documented), AD = A-level documentation (species with specimens deposited in scientific collections), and BD = B-level documentation (species documented with photographs or audio recordings). Source: this study (1), Lopes et al. 2016 (2), Kantek and Onuma 2013 (3), specimens deposited in the Department of Zoology of the Universidade Federal de Minas Gerais (4), and Brazil 2017 (5); Secondary list species in brackets. VU = Vulnerable (IUCN 2019) and VU* = Vulnerable (Brasil 2018)." pageId="15" pageNumber="416">2</tableCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA436C87C34FFA4FC89FAA0FB884CEB" blockId="15.[811,1420,1321,1758]" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">
<emphasis id="B96FEADA7C34FFA4FC89FAA0FC224FBB" bold="true" box="[813,974,1398,1422]" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">IDentificAtion.</emphasis>
This species was detected in all periods, mostly by voice. It was rarely seen but frequently heard. This species was observed making short flights and discreet landings among aquatic macrophytes (
<taxonomicName id="4C1B4D4B7C34FFA4FAF3FA0DFC444C21" authorityName="Kunth" authorityYear="1816" class="Liliopsida" family="Pontederiaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Commelinales" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Pontederiaceae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B4D4B7C34FFA4FC45FA2AFB944C21" box="[993,1144,1532,1556]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Polygonaceae</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B4D4B7C34FFA4FB28FA2AFAA44C21" authorityName="Least Bittern WA" baseAuthorityName="Gmelin" baseAuthorityYear="1789" box="[1164,1352,1532,1556]" class="Aves" family="Ardeidae" genus="Ixobrychus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pelecaniformes" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="exilis">
<emphasis id="B96FEADA7C34FFA4FB28FA2AFAA44C21" box="[1164,1352,1532,1556]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">Ixobrychus exilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a characteristic voice and vocalises frequently. This species is a small, reddish-brown bittern, with two white stripes on the back. The male has a black cap and back, with yellowish stripes on the throat, while the female has a brown cap and back, with the darkest bands on the neck (Martínez-Vilata et al. 2018).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
